Shodan may be used to find and exploit vulnerabilities in critical infrastructure systems, according Restrictions Reason 1. This offers a huge security concern since it may be used to launch cyberattacks against power grids, water treatment facilities, and other vital infrastructure. Shodan may also be used to collect sensitive personal data, such as IP addresses, login passwords, and other private information. This may lead to identity theft and other crimes. Permit Justification: Shodan may be used for valid cybersecurity research and vulnerability evaluations. It may assist find and repair system vulnerabilities, enhancing system security. Except for approved cybersecurity researchers and vulnerability assessors, the use of Shodan-like programs is prohibited for all persons and organizations. These approved persons and entities are required to acquire formal approval from the relevant authorities and to adhere to stringent data use, management, and reporting rules. Any unlawful usage of tools comparable to Shodan will result in swift legal action. 